2) Evaluation of the two candidates against those preferences:
- Late‑70s/early‑80s hard‑rock (CD 1): Positives for me include analog warmth, transient‑preserving mastering and upfront vocal immediacy. However, the mix is described as mid‑forward crunchy riffs with muscular low‑mids, thick riff‑and‑drum punch and tight driving drums — a clearly riff‑ and rhythm‑forward presentation. Even though the vocals are upfront, the emphasis on heavy riff punch, driving drums and muscular low‑mids runs counter to my preference for restrained percussion and mixes that prioritize vocal intimacy and midrange detail. That thicker, riff‑and‑drum emphasis increases the risk that layered low‑mids and percussion will compete with or mask subtle vocal nuance I care about.
