Evaluation of the two candidates against those criteria
- Tattoo You (midrange‑forward analogue rock):
  - Positives relative to my tastes: preserved transients and dynamics, punchy transient drums, tight low end, clear instrument separation and low‑compression mastering — all are good for transient detail and headroom.
  - Mismatches: the album’s “weathered immediate vocals” and prominent multi‑tracked sing‑along harmonies run counter to my dislike of thick multi‑tracked harmonies that reduce vocal immediacy. The description’s “natural room ambience” signals more room/air than I prefer (I favor minimal reverb and very front‑of‑mix phrasing). The riff‑led 3–5 minute studio takes emphasize band interplay and extended riffs (3–5 min) rather than the tight, hook‑first 3–4‑minute vocal‑forward pop forms I prefer. In short, while it preserves dynamics, its multi‑tracked harmonies and room ambience lean away from my vocal‑centric, clarity‑first preference.
